Title: Tea Pink with Khaki Cotton Quilt Cover Set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 and 80s is 18 .The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: Twill CottonColour: Tea Pink + KhakiDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Quilt covers 245cm x 210cm (King) / 210cm x 210cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

Title: Pure Jade Cotton Quilt Cover Set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 m and 80s is 18 m.The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: Long Staple CottonColour: Pure JadeDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Quilt covers 245cm x 210cm (King) / 210cm x 210cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 m and 80s is 18 m.The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: New Cotton 100SColour: Olive GreenDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Fitted sheets 180cm x 203cm x 40cm (King) / 152cm x 203cm x 40cm (Queen)1 x Flat sheets 275cm x 260cm (King) / 245cm x 260cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

Title: Pink with White Strip Cotton Quilt Cover Set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 and 80s is 18 .The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: 100% Washed CottonColour: Pink with White StripDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Quilt covers 245cm x 210cm (King) / 210cm x 210cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 and 80s is 18 m.The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. Title: Purple Pink With Light Grey Cotton Quilt Cover Set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 and 80s is 18 m.The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: Twill CottonColour: Purple Pink + Light GreyDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Quilt covers 245cm x 210cm (King) / 210cm x 210cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

Title: Star Blue Cotton Sheet Set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 and 80s is 18 .The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: Long Staple CottonColour: Star BlueDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Fitted sheets 180cm x 203cm x 40cm (King) / 152cm x 203cm x 40cm (Queen)1 x Flat sheets 275cm x 260cm (King) / 245cm x 260cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

Title: Indigo Cotton Sheet Set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 m and 80s is 18 .The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: New Cotton 100SColour: IndigoDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Fitted sheets 180cm x 203cm x 40cm (King) / 152cm x 203cm x 40cm (Queen)1 x Flat sheets 275cm x 260cm (King) / 245cm x 260cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

Title: Lite Grey Cotton Sheet set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 m and 80s is 18 m.The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: New Cotton 100SColour: Lite GreyDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Fitted sheets 180cm x 203cm x 40cm (King) / 152cm x 203cm x 40cm (Queen)1 x Flat sheets 275cm x 260cm (King) / 245cm x 260cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement

Title: Light Green Sateen Quilt Cover Set
Description: Product Details:Create a sumptuous sleep space with our range of designer bed linen. From soft and patterned cotton to opulent silk you can find the perfect bed linen range for your sleeping needs. With an array of luxury bed linen sets along with individual pieces, you can mix and match designs and styles to create your own unique look.Features:Yarn Size Vs Thread Count:All things being equal, (cotton type, mill, ply and weave), higher thread counts imply a smoother, silkier, and often more expensive fabric. But this can be misleading...Yarn size is stated as number, like 40s, 80s and 100s for most bed linen. The number refers to the yarn size (100s is finer than 40s) and is defined using micrometres . 100s is 17 and 80s is 18 .The thread count is the number of thread per square inch of fabric. For a given yarn size, a higher thread count implies a finer thread (sometimes).Because its thread is finer, 80s fabric has a higher thread count than 40s, and 100s fabric has a higher thread count than 80s, and so on. If you ask us what the thread-count of a fabric is, we will probably tell you something like "100s" ecause that number is easy to understand even though it's not a literal measure of thread-count. The yarn size (and its length per pound) is a consistent measure. It does not vary by the tightness of the weave or the counting method.Yarns, Ply and Counting:Ply is the number of yarns that are twisted together to make a single thread. Fabrics can either be two-ply or single ply. Two-ply means that two yarns are twisted together to make a single thread woven into the fabric. Two-ply fabrics may be superior to single-ply fabrics, but the smaller yarn size may make them less durable.Some manufacturers will count the individual yarns as they calculate the "thread count", so you may not be getting any extra thread just by buying higher thread-count material. Thread counts of 400 or more are likely to use multi-ply threads, which are more expensive and less durable (with limited benefits).Compact Vs Normal Yarns:A compact yarn is a higher quality yarn that is smoother and finer than a normal yarn. Fabrics woven from compact yarns often feel finer and smoother than you would expect based on their yarn size alone. For example, a 100s single-ply compact fabric will feel like a 160s two-ply fabric made from normal yarns.Warp and Weft:Warp threads run vertically. Weft yarns run horizontally. A fabric will often use different types of threads in the warp vs. weft directions. The total count of yarns (not threads) used in both waft and weft are used by some manufacturers as the thread-count.Specifications:Materials: Satin Cotton 60SColour: Light GreenDimensions: King / QueenCare instructions: wash separately before first use; cold machine wash on gentle cycle; do not bleach, rub or wring; line dry only in shade; warm iron on reverse whilst linen is still slightly damp; do not dry cleanPackage Included:1 x Quilt covers 245cm x 210cm (King) / 210cm x 210cm (Queen)2 x Pillowcases 50cm x 75cm (King) / 50cm x 75cm (Queen)Notes:The colors may be a little different for the different monitor display.Please allow minor deviation due to manual measurement
